            <tei:div type="commentary" xml:lang="eng" resp="Francesca Murano">
                <tei:note>
                    <tei:p>The stamp was part of the collection of <tei:ref target="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonifacio_Chiovitti">Bonifacio Chiovitti</tei:ref>; it has been lost and is only known through the Chiovitti's manuscipts. As reported by Chiovitti, the stamp was found «Extra Bovianum in hortis Varrianorum pone Ecclesiam S. Mariae de Vivarii; repertum hieme 1879» ['Outside of Bovianum, in the gardens of the Varrians, behind the Church of Santa Maria dei Vivarii; discovered in the winter of 1879.']. Due to urban expansion, the church is now located within the modern settlement.</tei:p>
                    <tei:p>According to <tei:ref target="http://zotero.org/groups/2552746/items/IKUTPHDC"><tei:bibl>Crawford, ImIt 2011</tei:bibl></tei:ref>: 1126, it is possible that this stamp has the same text present on the series of stamps on tile found in Spinete (Campobasso), loc. Masseria Strada Vecchia [inscriptions ItAnt Oscan nos. 412-482].</tei:p>
                    <tei:p><tei:rs type="name" xml:lang="osc-Ital-x-oscetr" corresp="Osc_419_l_1_w_1">ker</tei:rs> could be interpreted as the abbreviation of a persanal name, to be solved in the genitive case, presumably referring to the owner of the brick factory, or as the name of the goddess <tei:ref target="https://doi.org/10.1093/acrefore/9780199381135.013.1489">Ceres</tei:ref>, presumably gen. sg. In the latter case, it is reasonable to assume the existence of a temple dedicated to the goddess in the area of the monastery.</tei:p> 
                </tei:note>              
            </tei:div>
